<section xml:id="direction" version="5.0" xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"
                                             xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                                             xmlns:xl="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" >
  	<title>Direction</title>
  
  	<table>
  		<title>DIRECTION</title>
  		<tgroup cols="4" align="left" colsep="1" rowsep="1">
  			<thead>
  				<row>
  					<entry align="center">Parameter Name</entry>
  					<entry align="center">Data Type</entry>
  					<entry align="center">Possible Values</entry>
  					<entry align="center">Default</entry>	
  				</row>
  			</thead>
  			<tbody>
  				<row>
  					<entry>DIRECTION</entry>
  					<entry>String</entry>
  					<entry>
  						<itemizedlist>
  							<listitem><para>up</para></listitem>
  							<listitem><para>down</para></listitem>
  							<listitem><para>right</para></listitem>
  							<listitem><para>left</para></listitem>
  						</itemizedlist>
  					</entry>
  					<entry>right</entry>
  				</row>
  			</tbody>
  		</tgroup>
  	</table>
  	<itemizedlist>
  		<listitem><para>Use this parameter to define the direction you want to move/swipe in.</para></listitem>
  		<listitem><para>Combined with the cell/node count you can move any number of cells/nodes in any
  		direction.</para></listitem>
  		<listitem><para>For iOS applications you can define the direction you want a swipe to be performed on the
  		desired component. Direction means the direction in which the finger would swipe, e.g. 
  		<emphasis>left</emphasis> means that the swipe is performed from right to left on the component.</para></listitem>
  	</itemizedlist>
  
  
</section>